t-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">operate on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an equal footing with the independent sector. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Shed Media believes that if the BBC do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> invest in new technologies, such devices (such as the iPlayer) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">then these technologies should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">comm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ercialised as fully as possible and tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t the BBC should work in partnership with external technology companies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Response To The Inquiry Questions:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The issue of how the BBC balances </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">what the BBC produces in-house, what it commissions externally and what it leaves entirely to others to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> create</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of great importance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the broadcast community.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Shed Media believes that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the BBC should broadcast the best programmes it can regardless of whether they are produced ‘in house’ or from external producers and therefore that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">open comp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in commissioning </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should lead to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">better economic conditions for the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and ultimately b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etter </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">value for money</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">license fee payers.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  As stated in the Executive Summary we do not believe the WOCC should act as a cap on external productions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with the exception of news and current affairs).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Shed Media Group is currently commissioned via the WOCC.  As the ‘independent quota’ is set at 25% and the ‘in-house’ production guarantee at 50%, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">WOCC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is the remaining 25% of qualifying network commissioned programming.  As noted in the introduction Shed Media do not qualify under the independent quota. It is Shed Media’s view that the Independent Producer definition is outdated and should be amended.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is also our view that there should not be a 25% cap on the commissioning of ‘non qualifying independent producers’ or of 50% in total on independent producers and ‘non qualifying independent producers’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Companies like Shed Media Group are often formed t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hrough a mixture of organic growth and acquisitions, as such they will have invested substantial amounts in capex, staff costs and training and development.  They may often have several substantial bases, often in areas where there is limited alternative m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">edia employment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ability for ‘non qualifying independent’ companies to continue to win business from the BBC is vital to the health of the entire production community, to the creative output of the BBC and to the wider UK economy which benefits not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only from national tax receipts, but also from the significant trickle down of BBC revenues into local communities.  As the media sector continues to consolidate this is likely to become an increasingly important issue for ‘non qualifying independent produ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cers’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s ability to commission producer’s like Shed Media on the Terms of Trade (as per the Communications Act 2004) is key to the success of the UK’s independent production sector both in the UK and increasingly abroad. The BBC will often commiss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion content that other broadcasters do not consider their remit or that is less commercial than other networks; a show </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">like Who Do You Think You Are? a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s it was originally envisaged would not have been commissioned by any other UK broadcaster.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Shed Media b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elieve that the Terms of Trade have been key in boosting the UK production industry and will continue to provide opportunities for the UK’s creative sector going forward as they return an asset to the Producer, on which the Producer can hedge risk and inve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Further to this point as stated in its Charter, one of the key ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Public Purposes of the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> ‘ is ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Representing the UK, its nations, regions and communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  In 2008 the BBC made the following </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commitments to growing regional production outside of London: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> 50% of network spend will be made outside London by 2016, that 17% of network spend will come from the Nations by 2016 and that, in the interim, 12% of sp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">end will come from the Nations by 2012’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For the past 13 years Shed Media Group has been a key producer of programming from the ‘Nations and Regions’ and is containing to expand it’s regional and national bases.  Waterloo Road (10</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> series) is produced in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Scotland, as is Impractical Jokers (2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> series).  Britain’s Empty Homes (5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> series) and The Choir: Sing While You Work (2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> series) are produced from Brighton.  The Voice (3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> series) is shot at the BBC studios in Salford, Manchester.  Discussions are on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">going with the BBC to produce the 10</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> series of ‘Don’t Tell The Bride’ regionally.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are a committed partner to the BBC’s efforts to authentically represent the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘Nations, Regions and C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommunities’ in its output and we believe this is best achieved via s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">upporting and encouraging long term development and production in the regions, nations and communities that the BBC seeks to represent.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  We would encourage the BBC to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continue ‘additional’ commissioning in the nationals and regions as well as instances whe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re existing programming is moved from within the M25 to the regions or nations.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is our experience that certain types of ‘Nations and Regions’ productions can place an additional fiscal burden on production companies.  Attracting the best staff, finding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> suitable premises, negotiating contracts with suppliers and factoring in travel costs can lead to significant additional expenses and risks.  On occasion we have benefitted from the BBC making long term commitments to particular programming in the regions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, we understand this policy may continue and would suggest that this, and other policies designed to stimulate and support  productions from the ‘nation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and regions’ would be of immen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se benefit to the BBC, the production community and the general viewing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">public.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The issue of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘Nations and Regions’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funding is part of a larger discussion about how the BBC allocates its resources:  What can the BBC afford to fund and what can’t it?  Should it be better funding certain programmes or channels at the expense of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">others?  And to what extent should external producers be sharing the cost and risk of producing programmes? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As we see it the BBC doesn’t currently fully fund many of the programmes it commissions from external producers at the outset.  Across nearly all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the genres and channels external production companies – such as Shed Media Group - are contributing towards the total programme budget for BBC productions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC allows the production company to recoup this deficit from international sales of the finish</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed programmes or via international sales of the format, however there is no guarantee that the production company will recoup the money that they have invested into the programme.  In particular it is very likely that a deficit will not be fully recouped o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n titles which have a limited international appeal or where the deficit is very large. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Therefore there may be less incentive to pitch or produce programming that cannot be easily sold into the international marketplace to the BBC.  This include children’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s programming, small </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">run dramas, and productions with significant amounts of archive footage, but may also include more mainstream formats  and brand - since there is not necessarily a correlation between critical reception, audience viewing figures and in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ternational sales or format potential.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s ongoing ability to fully fund programming is therefore particularly vital to ensure that a variety of production companies large and small continue to pitch and produce all types of programming into the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It may be that ultimately tough decisions may have to be taken with regards to what the BBC can and can’t afford to fund, though we do see encouraging examples of flexible funding scenarios emerging from the BBC such as ‘bulk series ordering’ that may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">help. The new management and business leaders at the BBC are beginning to acknowledge the need to look creatively at funding and commercial scenarios and these developing conversations and debates are key to the development of the creative industries.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nges to the BBC’s commercial guidelines and remit are essential to allow change and encourage entrepreneurship both within the BBC as a functional business unit and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">out within the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">production sector to encourage producers to dialogue with the BBC. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Real cha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nge is being signalled by new BBC management </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will take time to see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant movement</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, Shed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">believes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that new BBC management have shown encouraging signs in this area.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would like to acknowledge the importance of BBC3, not simply as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">place for purposeful youth broadcasting and possibly the only home for youth current affairs and documentaries, but also because it provide as an invaluable place away from the headlights of BBC1 and BBC2 where talented producers and presenters can hone th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eir craft.  Our relationship with BBC3 dates back to its birth and many of our key creatives worked as junior producers for the channel on awarding winning titles such as: Blood Sweat &amp; ...  World’s Strictest Parents, Don’t Tell The Bride, Stacey Dooley In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vestigates... Cherry Healey.... BBC3 continues to be a place to grow and experiment and we believe its continued funding is important to the future health of the BBC and the media industry as a whole.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>